{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1b9de729-4f24-426b-a5e3-dbba05aceb72","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Event flow (typical):**\n\n| Transition | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| Sent to background | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| Returned to foreground | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` → `Destroying` |\n| iOS backgrounding | `Backgrounding` (save state via `e.State`) |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS-specific and provides a `BackgroundingEventArgs.State` dictionary you can use to persist transient data across termination.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f76010a-3c5d-49e2-b210-8f6df61d7ff9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging purposes. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development — I can answer this directly without needing to search files or run commands.","outputTokens":447,"requestId":"5011:BD0FA:1C19F9B:1F1E9C5:69FA904F"},"id":"f353de94-5e3c-448d-94f2-1320ec6acb82","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:50:32.822Z","parentId":"e1e867df-be88-459b-a738-2d87c0456baf"}
